pgTitle: List of former Royal Air Force stations

rows.text: HQ No. 14 Balloon Unit (and HQ Cardiff Group Royal Observer Corps from 1953 to 1968). Name changed to RAF Llandaff in 1946.
Airship station and gas production Maintenance Unit. Historic Airship hangars remain.
Briefly known as RAF Loch Erne between 1941 – 1943. Sunderland flying boat base in World War II.
Now used by the British Army
Bombing Ranges Unit with an Emergency Landing Ground
Now in the Republic of Ireland
Balloon station, also aircraft. Site considered for WWII ALG
Airship station, previously RNAS Capel-le-Ferne. Site used for a wireless station during WWII

Operated as a Medical Training Unit. Originally part of RAF Warton, but, in 1947, following the sale of the main Warton Airfield site to the English Electric Company, the site used as a Medical Training Unit became part of RAF Lytham. When RAF Lytham closed in 1956, the site continued to offer Medical Training and was designated as RAF Freckleton.
(Formerly RNAS Freiston – became an RAF station in 1918)
Airship and seaplane base, also known as RAF Port Victoria
Airfield redeveloped into Graham Park housing estate (early 1970s-on) and RAF Museum.
Co-located with RN Fleet Air Arm station HMS Godwit. Specialised in instrument and blind landing technologies.
Now used by the British Army
(Formerly RNAS Immingham – transferred to RAF in 1918)
(pre-RAF) RNAS Airship station, then RAF Isle of Grain
Part of the site is now HMP Kirkham
Also served as Lympne Airport between the wars and post WWII and HMS Buzzard / HMS Daedalus II from 1938–40

Originally part of RAF Warton, but when the main Airfield site was sold to the English Electric Company in 1947, one of the outlying sites was designated as RAF Lytham, and was used as a Transit Camp and for Medical Training. This site closed in 1956, with the Medical Traing Unit moving to another nearby site with the designated name of RAF Freckleton.
Now the site of the Fire Service College
It was also known locally as Tranwell
now Albermarle Barracks Royal Marines near Heddon on the Wall
Also known for a short period as RAF Childs Ercall. Later renamed HMS Godwit as a Fleet Air Arm instrument landing school
Aldenham Lodge Hotel requistioned as the headquarters of No. 80 (Signals) Wing
1938 location of No 23 Elementary and Reserve Flying Training School.
Originally an RFC station, used occasionally as a RLG in Second World War
Now used by Army, currently home to a Royal Artillery Regiment
Allocated as a WWII Emergency Landing Ground, but not used.
(Former RFC Aerodrome Tydd St Mary – Transferred to RAF in 1918)
training camp on the Wirral Peninsula
National Museum of Science and Industry
